<p>Since that initial TIE over a decade ago, thirty eight companies have participated in the TIE process.  Many mechanics of the TIE have changed over the years such as the addition of secure video teleconference connections for the TRADOC Centers of Excellence, U.S. Army Research, Development and Engineering Command and Headquarters, Department of the Army in 2011, and formalizing the roles and tasks for members of ARCIC and TRADOC under a TRADOC Task Order in August 2014.</p>
<p>To help focus discussion, participants are asked to relate the proposed capabilities to Army Warfighting Challenges (AWFCs), Learning Demands, and the Army Operating Concept.  All of these are available within this site.</p>
<p>One thing that has remained constant after 100 TIEs is the founding goal for this program which is to establish a dialogue with industry on corporate/company IRAD investment.  Events like the TIE provide us an opportunity to clarify future force development priorities to inform IRAD allocation.  They also allow Combat and Concept Developers to understand emerging technologies with potential application to military operations and to identify ways that TRADOC can simplify and improve the concepts to capabilities process.</p>
<p>During the TIE event, TRADOC can identify ideas to include in the Campaign of Learning as well as help industry to refine ideas and prototypes by identifying opportunities for participating in experiments such as the Army Expeditionary Warrior Experiment, Network Integration Experiment, Army Warfighting Assessment, etc.</p>
